<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911226-0021</DOCNO><DOCID>911226-0021.</DOCID><HL>   International Brief -- Lasmo PLC:   Company Plans to Cut Off   Ultramar Refining Assets</HL><DATE>12/26/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5</SO><CO>   U.LSM U.UMA</CO><MS>ENERGY (ENE)</MS><IN>OIL-SECONDARY (OIS)PETROLEUM (PET)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>PETROLEUM MARKET (PET)ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>CANADA (CN)EUROPE (EU)NORTH AMERICA (NME)GREAT BRITAIN (UK)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   Lasmo PLC, the British oil exploration and productioncompany, announced plans to &quot;disengage&quot; the North Americanrefineries and other &quot;downstream&quot; assets of Ultramar PLC.   Lasmo gained majority control of Ultramar last week aftera takeover battle.</LP><TEXT>   Lasmo said its long-term strategy is to remain &quot;a pureupstream exploration and production company,&quot; and that itplans to establish Ultramar's North American units --Ultramar Canada Inc. and Ultramar Inc. -- as separatebusinesses.   It said it has no plans to scale back or disrupt theoperations of either company.   Instead, Lasmo said, &quot;a range of divestment options arebeing considered.&quot; The options include selling the companiesor issuing shares in them.   The combined eastern Canada and western U.S. operationshave been estimated by analysts to be worth up to $1.5billion.   Ultramar's North American downstream operations includepetroleum product retail and wholesale marketing operationsin Quebec, Ontario, Newfoundland and Nova Scotia with averagesales volumes in 1990 of 122,000 barrels a day of gasolineand middle distillates. It is the leading gasoline marketerin eastern Canada.</TEXT></DOC>